{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"Own transient-failure retries at the httpx transport layer (`AsyncTenacityTransport`) so a mid-agentic-run blip self-heals below the agent graph, without re-executing already-run (side-effecting) tools. The transport-injection spike (GO, both paths) de-risks this load-bearing integration point.\n\n## Why\nA transient 429/529/5xx during a tool-using gate op must recover WITHOUT restarting the agent loop — a restart re-posts side-effecting tool calls and multiplies token cost. The community answer (pydantic-ai retries doc; Anthropic/OpenAI SDKs) is per-request retry at the HTTP transport, which re-sends only the one failed HTTP call while completed tool results are untouched. This is the riskiest integration point in the epic, verified by a spike (below) before the rest is built on it.\n\n## What\n### Dependency\nAdd the `retries` extra to the existing agents dep — spell it `pydantic-ai-slim[anthropic,retries]>=1,<2` (combined extras) in `pyproject.toml:108`. `[retries]` is a CONFIRMED extra (experiment log [1]) that ships `pydantic_ai.retries.AsyncTenacityTransport` + `wait_retry_after` and pulls in `tenacity` (confirmed installed at 9.1.4 by the spike). AC verifies `make install` provisions tenacity.\n\n### The single unified Anthropic construction (covers ALL paths, not just loopback)\nTODAY a custom `AnthropicProvider(base_url=_direct)` is built ONLY inside the loopback-proxy-bypass branch (`runner.py:233-240`, guarded by `self._model_override is None and resolved.startswith(\"anthropic\")` AND a non-empty `_direct`); the normal model-string path lets pydantic-ai build its own provider internally (SDK default retries, no transport). Refactor to a SINGLE helper that, for any REAL anthropic model resolved on the normal or loopback path, builds the client below. The offline `model_override` test seam is a NON-anthropic FunctionModel and is untouched (it never enters this construction). So the unified helper covers BOTH real paths that today diverge (normal = SDK-managed provider, loopback = custom base_url); after this story both share one retrying client:\n```\nAnthropicModel(name, provider=AnthropicProvider(anthropic_client=AsyncAnthropic(\n    base_url=<_direct or the SDK default>, max_retries=0,\n    http_client=httpx.AsyncClient(transport=AsyncTenacityTransport(config=RetryConfig(...), wrapped=<default httpx transport>, validate_response=<callback>)))))\n```\nThe loopback bypass just varies `base_url` (direct vs default); both paths get the SAME retrying client. `AnthropicProvider.__init__(api_key, base_url, anthropic_client, http_client)` confirmed (experiment log [4]); `AsyncAnthropic` accepts `max_retries` + `http_client` (log [5]).\n\n### Retry config (proven by the spike)\n- `RetryConfig(retry=retry_if_exception_type(httpx.HTTPStatusError) | retry_if_exception_type(httpx.TimeoutException) | retry_if_exception_type(httpx.ConnectError), wait=wait_retry_after(fallback_strategy=None, max_wait=<verify.llm_retry_max_wait_s>), stop=stop_after_attempt(<verify.llm_retry_max_attempts>), reraise=True)`.\n- `wait_retry_after(fallback_strategy=None, max_wait=...)` — `fallback_strategy` DEFAULTS to None (verified: signature `(fallback_strategy=None, max_wait=300)`); None means \"use tenacity's default backoff when no `Retry-After` header is present,\" and the header (capped at `max_wait`) is honored when present.\n- `validate_response(response)` callback turns retriable STATUS CODES into exceptions (they are not exceptions by default): `def validate_response(resp): if resp.status_code in {429, 529, 500, 502, 503, 504}: resp.raise_for_status()` — raising `httpx.HTTPStatusError`, which the `retry` predicate catches. **529 is included explicitly** (pydantic-ai's sample list omits it). Signature + behavior proven by the spike.\n- `reraise=True` re-raises the last attempt's ORIGINAL exception on exhaustion (story mamba's classifier additionally unwraps a `tenacity.RetryError` defensively for the edge paths — complementary).\n\n### Construction-time guard (no silent downgrade)\nThe transport-injection assertion fires at MODEL-CONSTRUCTION time inside `PydanticAIRunner.run()` (NOT process startup — the model is built lazily per run): assert the `AsyncAnthropic` client was built with `max_retries == 0` AND our retrying transport is present; if injection ever fails to apply, FAIL FAST rather than silently regress to the SDK default. The spike asserts `anthropic_client.max_retries == 0`.\n\n### Config keys (added to LLMConfig — the runner's own config object)\nAdd `llm_retry_max_attempts: int = 4` and `llm_retry_max_wait_s: int = 60` to `LLMConfig` in `src/rebar/llm/config.py` — NOT VerifyConfig. Rationale (code-grounded): `PydanticAIRunner.run()` receives an `LLMConfig`, and every existing LLM OPERATIONAL knob (`timeout_s`, `max_tokens`, `max_iterations`) already lives on `LLMConfig` with a `REBAR_LLM_*` env fallback; `[verify]` holds verification-GATE semantic toggles, not model-runtime knobs. So add fields + `from_env` lines using `_llm_int(table, cli, \"REBAR_LLM_RETRY_MAX_ATTEMPTS\", \"llm_retry_max_attempts\", 4)` and `_llm_int(table, cli, \"REBAR_LLM_RETRY_MAX_WAIT_S\", \"llm_retry_max_wait_s\", 60)`, read from the `[llm]` table. Threaded into the RetryConfig above at construction. Documented in `docs/config.md`.\n- **Opt-out semantics (precise):** `cfg.llm_retry_max_attempts <= 1` makes `stop_after_attempt(1)` — the transport makes ONE attempt and does NOT retry. Combined with the always-on SDK `max_retries=0`, that is ZERO retries total: a deliberate FAIL-FAST. This does NOT restore the old undeliberate SDK 2-retry behavior (that inheritance is intentionally replaced by owned, config-controlled retry) — the toggle is \"retry vs no-retry,\" not \"new vs legacy.\"\n\n### Retry observability\nEach retry attempt (status/exception, attempt number, Retry-After wait) and final exhaustion log at WARNING (quiet by default), so a flaky provider window is visible without a debugger — via the transport's `validate_response`/wait hooks or a `before_sleep` callback on the RetryConfig.\n\n### AsyncClient lifecycle\nThe `httpx.AsyncClient` holds a connection pool. Construct it per-run alongside the model (bounded to the run's lifetime) and ensure it does not leak across runs; if a shared/cached client is used, its shutdown is handled. AC asserts no unclosed-client resource warning across a run.\n\n### Comment idempotency — NO new work (already solved)\n`comment_verdict` (`src/rebar/llm/workflow/steps.py:260-284`) ALREADY embeds a `[rebar-run <run_id>/<step_id>]` marker and skips a duplicate within the same run. Because transport-level retry re-sends only the failed HTTP request BELOW the agent loop, completed tool calls (comments) are NEVER re-executed by a retry in the first place. So this story adds NO comment-tool change; it only ASSERTS (test) that a mid-run 429->200 self-heal posts no duplicate comment, which the existing marker + transport-level retry already guarantee.\n\n### Streaming out of scope\nThe runner uses buffered `agent.run_sync()` (no streaming), so mid-stream partial-byte retry is not applicable; retries operate on whole buffered request/response pairs.\n\n### ADR\nThe novel decision (retry at the httpx transport with SDK `max_retries=0`, justified by side-effect-safety — already-run tools are not repeated) is captured. To avoid a cross-story doc-ownership split, this story writes a short ADR stub at `docs/adr/0037-transport-retry.md` (0037 is the next free number — 0026 is already taken by two existing ADRs; blackbear, the sole ADR/docs owner, finalizes/renumbers if needed); an AC covers the stub's presence.\n\n\n### Notes on prior art, resources, and the fixed status set\n- **Distinct from the reconciler's HTTP retry.** `_call_with_retry` (in the Jira/git reconciler) retries the RECONCILER's outbound HTTP at a different layer for a different peer; this story's transport retry is scoped to the LLM MODEL client only. They do not overlap or share config.\n- **AsyncClient lifecycle (concrete).** The `httpx.AsyncClient` is created together with the `AnthropicModel` inside `PydanticAIRunner.run()` and is bounded to that run; it is explicitly closed at the end of the run (try/finally or an `aclose()` on teardown) so no connection pool leaks across runs — asserted by a no-unclosed-client-warning test.\n- **The retriable status set {429,529,500,502,503,504} is intentionally FIXED in code**, not a config surface — it is the well-known transient-HTTP set; exposing it as a knob would be scope creep with no operator need. `verify`/`llm` config governs only attempts + wait cap.\n\n## Scope\n- Dependency + the unified retrying-client construction (owned here; story chief-contained-hoopoe passes its `httpx.Timeout` INTO this same `httpx.AsyncClient` — this story is the named client-construction owner so the two settings merge on one client) + construction-time guard + the two config keys + docs + retry observability + client lifecycle + the spike.\n- NOT in scope: message-history-replay resume (future Tier-2); streaming retry (no streaming); the per-tool/read TIMEOUT values (hoopoe); exit-code/gate posture (blackbear); any comment-tool change (already idempotent).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `pydantic-ai-slim[anthropic,retries]>=1,<2` in `pyproject.toml`; `make install` provisions `tenacity` (asserted).\n- [ ] The spike integration test proves a `429`(+`Retry-After`)->`200` sequence is retried at the transport layer BELOW the SDK, honoring `Retry-After`, within one agent turn, on BOTH the normal and loopback-bypass base_url paths; AND a `500`(NO `Retry-After`)->`200` sequence is retried via the `fallback_strategy=None` default backoff (so the no-header path is verified, not merely asserted).\n- [ ] The unified helper builds the retrying client for ANY anthropic model; SDK `max_retries=0` and transport-present are asserted by the construction-time guard (a test forces injection to fail and asserts FAIL-FAST, not silent downgrade).\n- [ ] 529 + the transient set {429,529,500,502,503,504} + httpx timeout/connect are retried; `Retry-After` honored and capped at `verify.llm_retry_max_wait_s`.\n- [ ] A mid-run transient (injected 429->200) self-heals and asserts NO duplicate comment (existing run-marker + transport retry).\n- [ ] `verify.llm_retry_max_attempts` / `verify.llm_retry_max_wait_s` exist on `VerifyConfig`, are read from `[verify]`, and default 4 / 60; a test sets `llm_retry_max_attempts=1` and asserts NO retry occurs (fail-fast opt-out), and the exhaustion path (all attempts fail) re-raises the original exception.\n- [ ] Retry attempts + exhaustion are logged (asserted via caplog); the AsyncClient does not leak (no unclosed-client warning across a run); an ADR stub exists at the placeholder path.\n- [ ] `make test`/`make lint`/`make typecheck` green.\n\nFiles: `pyproject.toml`, `src/rebar/llm/runner.py` (unified construction + guard + observability), `src/rebar/_config_schema.py` (two VerifyConfig keys + validators), `docs/config.md`, `docs/adr/0037-transport-retry.md` (stub), `tests/` (spike + config + guard + exhaustion + no-duplicate-comment).\n\n## Verified library behavior (experiment log — pydantic-ai 1.107.0, tenacity 9.1.4, anthropic SDK, offline)\nACTUAL captured output (no billable call):\n```\n[1] '[retries]' in pydantic-ai-slim Provides-Extra: True          (the extra is real)\n[2] wait_retry_after params: ['fallback_strategy', 'max_wait']     (standalone helper, honors Retry-After + caps)\n[3] AsyncTenacityTransport params: ['config', 'wrapped', 'validate_response']\n[4] AnthropicProvider.__init__ params: ['api_key', 'base_url', 'anthropic_client', 'http_client']\n[5] AsyncAnthropic accepts max_retries + http_client: True         (SDK max_retries=0 + inject our client)\n[6] tenacity installed: 9.1.4\n```\nSPIKE (the load-bearing proof; tmp/spike.py, re-run offline): an AsyncTenacityTransport in a custom\nhttpx.AsyncClient, forwarded through AnthropicProvider(anthropic_client=AsyncAnthropic(max_retries=0,\nhttp_client=...)), retries a 429(+Retry-After)->200 sequence BELOW the SDK under agent.run_sync():\n```\n[normal path] requests=2 output='SPIKE_OK' -> PASS\n[loopback-bypass path] requests=2 output='SPIKE_OK' -> PASS\nSPIKE RESULT: GO — transport injection retries 429->200 below the SDK under run_sync on both paths\n```\nThese are pydantic-ai/httpx/tenacity/anthropic LIBRARY symbols, not rebar symbols — a code-grounding\npass restricted to the rebar snapshot must not read their repo-absence as non-existence (bug\nsuccinct-formable-kite). The spike proves the architecture is sound BEFORE dependent stories build on it."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783649152203252001,"uuid":"7e01d673-6c5c-4769-bd47-286747cbc4e4"}